{XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"\"\"#F&F&,&F%F&F&!\"\"F&,(*&\"\"$F&)F%F'
F&F&F%F&F,F&F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 20 "factor(x^
5-x^2-2*x);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(%\"xG\"\"\",&F$F%F%F%
F%,**$)F$\"\"$F%F%*$)F$\"\"#F%!\"\"F$F%F-F.F%" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 650 "In those cases where Maple did not find enough linear fa
ctors, there is a reason why Maple did not.  Maple makes an assumption
 that if the coefficients of a polynomial are all given exactly (as in
tegers or rational numbers [ratios of integer]), then you are only int
erested in finding exact factors (factors where the coefficients are i
ntegers or rational numbers).  The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra does
n't guarantee that the factors of  a polynomial will necessarily have \+
the same kind of coefficients as the polynomial, only the polynomial c
an be factored.  You can force Maple to report additional (approximate
) factors.  For example,  compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 
"" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }
}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(h,sqrt(5));" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"*$\"\"&#F&\"\"#!\"\"F&,
&F%F&F'F&F&,&F%F&F&F&F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 52 "What is the difference?  The extra-term is called \+
a " }{TEXT 280 18 "field extension.  " }{TEXT -1 178 "Adding it tells \+
Maple to consider additonal factors where the coefficients are allowed
 to include elements from the field extension.  It is fairly clear fro
m the factoriztion of " }{TEXT 281 1 "h" }{TEXT -1 280 " all by itself
 that something involving  sqrt(5)  would have to be included.  Howeve
r, there are problems where there is not a obvious clue as to which sp
ecific field extension should be added.  If you are willing to accept \+
an appropriate solution, then using the field extension " }{TEXT 282 
4 "real" }{TEXT -1 179 " tells Maple to factor the polynomial using a \+
floating point approximation scheme.  For example, consider (here I am
 pretending I don't see that adding  sqrt(5) would be optimal):" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
13 "Digits := 10;" }}{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}{PARA 11 "
" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%'DigitsG\"#5" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"
xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "
" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "factor(h,real);" }}{PARA 12 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#
*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"$\"_qvAyy$3WT9%**[!yjD4_5aC(*3FCd_6'f$=1WNiFJ(oO<4kp*y*
\\xz1OA!#**F&F&,&F%F&$F&\"\"!F&F&,&F%F&$\"_qvAyy$3WT9%**[!yjD4_5aC(*3F
Cd_6'f$=1WNiFJ(oO<4kp*y*\\xz1OAF)!\"\"F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 91 "Finally, the Fundamental Theorem o
f Algebra does not guarantee that a polynomial of degree " }{TEXT 283 
1 "n" }{TEXT -1 11 " will have " }{TEXT 284 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 53 " real \+
linear factors.  Rather, only hat it will have " }{TEXT 285 1 "n" }
{TEXT -1 134 " linear factors.  What is the difference?  Some of the f
actors may involve complex roots rather than real roots.  For example \+
compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(F);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&*$)
%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F)\"#7!\"\"F),&F%F)F*F)F)" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "
" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(F,sqrt(3));" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 
"6#*(,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F)\"#7F)F),&F'F)*&F(F)\"\"$#F)F(!\"\"F),&F'F
)*&F(F)F-F.F)F)" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "factor(F
,real);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"$\"+:;5kM!\"
*F&F&,&F%F&$\"+:;5kMF)!\"\"F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&$\"+++++7!\")F&F&" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(F,complex);" }}{PARA 
11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#**,&%\"xG\"\"\"$\"+:;5kM!\"*F&F&,&F%F&^#F'F&
F&,&F%F&^#$!+:;5kMF)F&F&,&F%F&$\"+:;5kMF)!\"\"F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 126 "For the following polyno
mials demonstrate that each can be factored completely into linear fac
tors.  Use the field extensions " }{TEXT 286 4 "real" }{TEXT -1 5 " an
