0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 380 "A related theorem about finding roots of polyn
omials (equivalently factoring polynomials into a product of linear fa
ctors) asserts that if the polynomial has real coefficients -- all of \+
the polynomials we have considered (and will consider) have had real c
oefficients -- then any complex roots (or factors) must occur in conju
gate pairs.  For example, both the complex factors of " }{TEXT 288 5 "
F, G " }{TEXT -1 4 "and " }{TEXT 289 2 "H " }{TEXT -1 236 "(above) all
 occurred in conjugate pairs.  Demonstrate this theorem by creating th
ree new polynomials, name them F1, G1 and H1, of degree 5, 6 and 7, re
sp., and show that the any complex factors of F1, G1 and H1 occur in c
onjugate pairs." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> \+
" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 22 "F1:='3*x^5-x^3-2*x^2':" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
